  "text": "For elliptic particles, on the other hand, non-uniform pressure distribution around a particle becomes a major contributing factor for rotating motion. When an elliptic particle rotates, it has to displace the fluid and the first order moment of restitution force works to damp the rotating motion. Therefore, the swinging motions of the elliptic particles exhibit the sudden changes in rotating motion in a short period of time. . The present author [CITATION_1] has reported that spherical particles of disabled rotating mobility tend to form clusters (dense population zones). The above result suggests that the correlation between the rotation mobility and clusterisation may also apply to non-circular particles.",
